{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"06d01e05-cb48-46b6-a763-165dd2b0a13b","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs the **same versions** already recorded. It fixes corrupted or missing files but won't pull newer versions needed by an updated SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** After an SDK update, the workloads need *newer* packages, not a reinstall of the old ones. Run:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, a `dotnet workload repair` can clean up any residual corruption.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3aa07141-4f3d-4023-830e-d528c124330a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase for this.","outputTokens":253,"requestId":"103C:270DE0:1538C9E:17CB586:69FD33B9"},"id":"2f1a9ce9-8896-4050-a0fd-3e6f91b15cd9","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:52:18.631Z","parentId":"e30d0f32-7485-46ae-a9ae-d4b0baae247f"}
